    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div type="letter">
                <div type="text">
                    <opener>
                        <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                        <date>April 23<hi rend="superscript">d</hi></date>
                        <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                    </opener>
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p>On returning home after a week’s absence, I found your marriage cards.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I now understand your move to Richmond!<ref target="#foot.f3"/> Allow me to send you my very sincere congratulations on entering into that state which assuredly gives the best chance of true happiness in this world.</p>
                        <p>With every good wish &amp; my compliments to M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Oliver, pray believe me | Yours sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                
                
            </div>
           
           
           <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the date of Oliver’s marriage (see n. 2, below).</note>
                <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD was in London from 16 to 20 April 1861 (Emma Darwin’s diary (DAR 242)). Oliver married <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6457.xml">Hannah Hobson Wall</ref> in 1861.</note>
               <note xml:id="foot.f3">The 1861 census records Oliver living in Richmond, Surrey (Census returns of England and Wales 1861 (The National Archives: Public Record Office RG9/459/143/28)). Before that, he lived at Kew, presumably in lodgings (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5933.xml"><hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi></ref>).</note>
            </div>
        
